04625nam a22007215i 9780823277827DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232778277 a10.1515/97808232778272doi  a(DE-B1597)555174  a(OCoLC)1003259969  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB821b.P48 2018 7aSCI0750002bisacsh04a1442231 aPeterson, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMonkey Trouble :bThe Scandal of Posthumanism /cChristopher Peterson. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tcontents -- tIntroduction -- tchapter 1. The Scandal of the Human -- tchapter 2. Sovereign Silence -- tchapter 3. The Gravity of Melancholia -- tchapter 4. Listing Toward Cosmocracy -- tacknowledgments -- tnotes -- tbibliography -- tindex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aAccording to scholars of the nonhuman turn, the scandal of theory lies in its failure to decenter the human. The real scandal, however, is that we keep trying.The human has become a conspicuous blind spot for many theorists seeking to extend hospitality to animals, plants, and even insentient things. The displacement of the human is essential and urgent, yet given the humanist presumption that animals lack a number of allegedly unique human capacities, such as language, reason, and awareness of mortality, we ought to remain cautious about laying claim to any power to eradicate anthropocentrism altogether. Such a power risks becoming yet another self-accredited capacity thanks to which the human reaffirms its sovereignty through its supposed erasure.Monkey Trouble argues that the turn toward immanence in contemporary posthumanism promotes a cosmocracy that absolves one from engaging in those discriminatory decisions that condition hospitality as such. Engaging with recent theoretical developments in speculative realism and object-oriented ontology, as well as ape and parrot language studies, the book offers close readings of literary works by J.M. Coetzee, Charles Chesnutt, and Walt Whitman and films by Alfonso Cuarón and Lars von Trier.Anthropocentrism, Peterson argues, cannot be displaced through a logic of reversal that elevates immanence above transcendence, horizontality over verticality. This decentering must cultivate instead a human/nonhuman relationality that affirms the immanent transcendency spawned by our phantasmatic humanness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aHuman beings. 0aHuman-animal relationships. 0aHumanismxPhilosophy. 0aHumanism. 0aNature and civilization. 0aPhilosophical anthropology. 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh  aAlfonso Cuarón.  aCharles Chesnutt.  aEdmund Husserl.  aJ.M. Coetzee.  aJacques Derrida.  aLars von Trier.  aObject Oriented Ontology.  aPosthumanism.  aSpeculative Realism.  aWalt Whitman.  aanimal studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107290160 cprintz978082327779740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823277827?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823277827zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823277827/original  a978-3-11-072901-6 Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA